SIMPLE: popinjay
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Popinjay
<hw>Pop"in*jay</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>popingay</ets>, <ets>papejay</ets>, OF. <ets>papegai</ets>,
<ets>papegaut</ets>; cf. Pr. <ets>papagai</ets>, Sp. & Pg.
<ets>papagayo</ets>, It. <ets>pappagallo</ets>, LGr. <?/, NGr. <?/; in
which the first syllables are perhaps imitative of the bird's chatter,
and the last either fr. L. <ets>gallus</ets> cock, or the same word as
E. <ets>jay</ets>, F. <ets>geai</ets>. Cf. <er>Papagay</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The green
woodpecker.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A parrot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The pye and <qex>popyngay</qex> speak they know not what.</q>
<rj><qau>Tyndale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A target in the form of a parrot.</def>
<mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A trifling, chattering, fop or coxcomb.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧To be so pestered with a <xex>popinjay</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Popish</ent>⟦br⟧
